  "texts": [
    "While these two decision procedures make little difference with regards to runtime-like our solution to c2, both take O(no) time, where o refers to the number of outcomes for each action-they make a significant moral difference.",
    "However, like c1-c4, c5 still assumes some sort of Bayesian oracle, which is able to infer the exact posterior probabilities that certain events (outcomes) will occur given certain causes (actions).",
    "More broadly, causal inference can be understood as the ability to identify what causes what, e.g., \"what is the cause (or causes) of phenomenon X?",
    "\", \"what is the effect (or effects) of Y?",
    "\", and \"what is the causal relationship between X and Y?\"."
  ],
